      body:
        "Two more methods round out the toolkit, so you can always **match the method to the mixture**.\n\n**Separating funnel** — for **two liquids that do not mix** (called **immiscible** liquids), such as **oil and water**. Left to stand, the liquids settle into two clear layers, with the less dense one (oil) floating on top. The mixture is poured into a separating funnel (a glass funnel with a tap at the bottom); you open the tap to let the lower layer drain out first, then close it just as the boundary reaches the tap, leaving the upper layer behind. This works because the liquids stay in separate layers instead of dissolving in each other.\n\n**Magnetic separation** — for a mixture where **one solid is magnetic** and the others are not, for example separating **iron filings** from sand or from sulfur powder. Holding a **magnet** over the mixture attracts and lifts out the iron, leaving the non-magnetic part behind. It only works for magnetic materials such as iron, steel, nickel and cobalt.\n\nSo before choosing a method, ask: are the substances solids, liquids or dissolved? Do they mix? And is one of them magnetic? The answer points you to the right technique.",
